{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8b29b5cd65669c66", "type": "tool_result", "content": "1\tCan Tokens Compete? Token Representations against\n2\tSupervised CNN Backbones for BirdCLEF+ 2026\n3\tAnthony Miyaguchi1,* , Murilo Gustineli1,* and Adrian Cheung1,*\n4\t1\n5\t\n6\tGeorgia Institute of Technology, 225 North Ave NW, Atlanta, GA 30332\n7\t\n8\tAbstract\n9\t\n10\tThis paper details the DS@GT ARC team’s approach to BirdCLEF+ 2026, multi-label detection of animal vocalizations in soundscapes from the Pantanal wetlands. The 2026 edition adds about an hour of labeled soundscapes,\n11\tshifting the task toward supervised pipelines fit to the labeled set. First, we build a competitive supervised\n12\tbaseline that ensembles a frozen Perch v2 backbone, a trained HGNetV2-B0 sound-event-detection network, and\n13\ta non-bird prototypical head, reaching a private leaderboard score of 0.936 at rank 1894 within a 90-minute CPU\n14\tbudget. Second, we ask whether token-based representations can compete, contrasting codec representations\n15\tfrom neural audio codecs against semantic representations from foundational embeddings. We compare two\n16\tbioacoustic specialist models against four token-based encoders trained on AudioSet. The repository for this\n17\twork can be found at https://github.com/dsgt-arc/birdclef-2026.\n18\t\n19\tKeywords\n20\t\n21\tBirdCLEF, Bioacoustics, Soundscape classification, Audio foundation models, Neural audio codecs\n22\t\n23\t1. Introduction\n24\tBirdCLEF+ [1] is a competition, hosted on Kaggle and organized through the LifeCLEF lab at the\n25\tConference and Labs of the Evaluation Forum (CLEF) [2], to build a model that detects and classifies\n26\tanimal vocalizations in soundscapes. Soundscapes are recordings of a landscape captured by autonomous\n27\trecording units deployed to the field. The 2026 edition of the competition is focused on multi-label\n28\tdetection on 60-second soundscapes from the Pantanal wetlands in South America.\n29\tThe largest challenge in the previous years was that while there were many recordings for each\n30\tspecies, they were weakly labeled. A given audio clip in the focal set contains vocalizations for a\n31\tparticular species, but the time range in which the vocalization occurs is not given, and there may also\n32\tbe multiple sources of sound. The focal recordings are also biased toward the most common species\n33\tthat can be found via population centers, because they are easier to capture and there are likely to be\n34\tmore people around to capture those sounds. This heavy-tailed distribution makes species with only a\n35\thandful of examples hard to learn, and the problem formulation encourages few-shot solutions.\n36\tThe 2026 edition of the competition added about an hour of labeled soundscapes, leading to a\n37\tsignificant change in the strategy for model development. Previous editions focused on the domain shift\n38\tfrom focal recordings taken from Xeno-canto [3], which are crowd-sourced, to the soundscape domain,\n39\twhich is multi-label and without provided ground truth. This means that supervised algorithms now\n40\tdominate the leaderboard and lean heavily into the small set of labeled data.\n41\tFirst, we build a supervised baseline system following the best practices established by the Kaggle\n42\tcommunity, leading to a competitive leaderboard submission on the labeled soundscape set for team\n43\tDS@GT ARC at rank 1894 with a score of 0.936. Second, we investigate whether token-based representations can be effective on this leaderboard, and compare the semantic representations produced by\n44\tfoundational audio embeddings against the reconstruction-oriented codec representations produced\n45\tby neural audio codecs. We close with discussion around a future of foundational systems capable of\n46\tcontextualizing soundscapes, beyond the domain of short focal recordings.\n47\tCLEF 2026: Conference and Labs of the Evaluation Forum, September 21-24, 2026, Jena, Germany\n48\tCorresponding author.\n49\t$ acmiyaguchi@gatech.edu (A. Miyaguchi); murilogustineli@gatech.edu (M. Gustineli); acheung@gatech.edu (A. Cheung)\n50\t https://murilogustineli.com (M. Gustineli)\n51\t\u001a 0000-0002-9165-8718 (A. Miyaguchi); 0009-0003-9818-496X (M. Gustineli); 0009-0006-8650-4550 (A. Cheung)\n52\t\n53\t*\n54\t\n55\t© 2026 Copyright for this paper by its authors. Use permitted under Creative Commons License Attribution 4.0 International (CC BY 4.0).\n56\t\n57\t\f2. Related Work\n58\tSoundscape recognition typically uses deep networks on audio spectrograms. The usual representation\n59\tis the mel-scaled short-time Fourier transform (STFT), which scales frequencies to the perceptual\n60\tscale of human hearing and is fed into convolutional networks (CNNs) whose spatial bias suits the\n61\tspectral structure of sound. BirdNET [4] and Perch v2 [5] are the state of the art, training CNNs to\n62\tproduce both windowed species occurrence probabilities and a reusable embedding space. Global\n63\tbirdsong embeddings demonstrate a large domain gap in transfer learning with respect to generalpurpose foundation models like AudioMAE for bioacoustics [6]. Self-supervised encoders like AVES\n64\t[7], benchmarks like BirdSet [8], and a recent comparative review [9] help contextualize efforts toward\n65\texploiting larger bioacoustic datasets.\n66\tWe study two families of token representations. Semantic embeddings come from self-supervised\n67\taudio models: AST [10] adapted vision transformers to spectrograms, BEATs [11] and EAT [12] improved\n68\tthis with masked prediction, wav2vec 2.0 [13] learns from speech, and Bird-MAE [14] adapts masked\n69\tautoencoding to birds. Codec representations come from neural audio codecs: SoundStream [15],\n70\tEnCodec [16], and the single-codebook WavTokenizer [17] are trained to reconstruct waveforms for\n71\thuman perception. We also test linear-time state-space models, where Mamba [18], SSAMBA [19], and\n72\trecent bioacoustic SSMs [20] scale to the long sequences needed to contextualize a full soundscape.\n73\tThe recurring difficulty in earlier editions was domain shift: focal recordings from Xeno-canto [3]\n74\thad to generalize to unlabeled multi-label soundscapes [21], and the 2026 labeled hour shifts this toward\n75\tsupervised pipelines fit to the labeled set. The DS@GT team has competed since 2022: motif mining [22]\n76\tin 2022 [23], transfer learning on BirdNET embeddings [24] in 2023 [25], sound-separation pseudo-labels\n77\t[26, 27] in 2024 [28], and a word2vec-style token model [29, 30] in 2025 [31]. We build upon these\n78\ttechniques, reusing the vectorized knowledge of models in sample-efficient ways.\n79\t\n80\t3. Data\n81\tBirdCLEF 2026 data contains 522.1 hours of audio, split between 344.5 h of focal recordings across\n82\t206 species and 177.6 h of soundscapes from 23 sites in the Pantanal, Brazil. Only 1.03 h (66 files, 739\n83\tunique 5 s windows, spanning 9 of the 23 sites) of the soundscape audio is labeled; the remaining 176.5 h\n84\tis unlabeled. Of the 234 target species, 28 are derived from soundscapes alone, many of those being\n85\tinsects. Only 2.4% of focal recordings come from the Pantanal bounding box, and 87 species have zero\n86\trecordings from Pantanal.\n87\t\n88\tFigure 1: Representative spectrograms of three vocalizing taxa in BirdCLEF 2026. The taxa overlap in frequency.\n89\tFrogs produce pulsed call trains, birds frequency-modulated whistles, and insects a sustained broadband droning\n90\tsound.\n91\t\n92\t\fTable 1\n93\tClass composition of the focal training set vs. the labeled soundscape windows. The focal training is mostly\n94\tbirds, while the soundscape is mostly amphibians. In the insect class, the focal species do not overlap with the\n95\tsoundscape species. Note that soundscape windows are multi-label, and thus the percentage of windows sums\n96\tup to a value greater than 100.\n97\t\n98\tClass\n99\tAves\n100\tAmphibia\n101\tInsecta\n102\tMammalia\n103\tReptilia\n104\t\n105\tFocal (recordings)\n106\t\n107\tSoundscape (windows)\n108\t\n109\tSpecies\n110\t\n111\t% recs\n112\t\n113\tSpecies\n114\t\n115\t% windows\n116\t\n117\t162\n118\t32\n119\t3\n120\t8\n121\t1\n122\t\n123\t97.89\n124\t1.27\n125\t0.56\n126\t0.28\n127\t0.003\n128\t\n129\t28\n130\t17\n131\t25\n132\t4\n133\t1\n134\t\n135\t28.7\n136\t76.6\n137\t22.7\n138\t5.5\n139\t1.8\n140\t\n141\tThe animal vocalizations are not necessarily separable by frequency band. Frogs, birds, and insects\n142\tall concentrate energy in 1–4 kHz and differ in spectro-temporal structure (Figure 1).\n143\tA statistical breakdown of the training and test data (Table 1) reiterates the challenges posed by the\n144\tcompetition and lab. The gap between recording domains, together with the long-tailed distribution of\n145\trecordings over species, means that models must be sample-efficient and account for the low-resource\n146\tnature of the data.\n147\t\n148\t4. Supervised Baseline System\n149\tThe 2026 data rewards supervised pipelines fit directly to the hour of labeled soundscape data, and we\n150\tfollow Kaggle community best practices to build a competitive baseline. The system is an ensemble\n151\tof a frozen Perch v2 [5] backbone with MLP probes whose probabilities are blended with a trained\n152\tHGNetV2-B0 sound-event-detection (SED) network. The best model, which includes a prototypical\n153\thead for non-bird species, reaches a public leaderboard score of 0.931 and a private score of 0.936 at\n154\trank 1894 (Figure 2, Table 2). Most score gains come from frontend and architecture choices rather than\n155\ttraining tricks or extra data, and we’ve aimed for a parsimonious system.\n156\tMember 1: frozen, probes only\n157\t\n158\tPerch v2 (frozen)\n159\t1536-d embedding\n160\t\n161\tMLP probes\n162\tlogit-space, 5-fold OOF\n163\t\n164\t0.920\n165\tprob-space blend\n166\t\n167\t60 s soundscape\n168\t\n169\t𝑤Perch =0.5\n170\t\n171\t→ 12 × 5 s windows\n172\t\n173\t0.922\n174\tHGNetV2-B0 SED\n175\tlog-mel, mixup, BCE\n176\t\n177\t4-fold + TTA\n178\t0.917\n179\t\n180\tsite/hour\n181\tpriors\n182\t+0.007\n183\t\n184\tnon-bird\n185\tmerge\n186\t+0.002\n187\t\n188\tsubmission\n189\t234 probs\n190\t\n191\t0.931\n192\t\n193\tnon-bird\n194\tprototypes\n195\t\n196\tMember 2: trained on audio\n197\t\n198\tFigure 2: The supervised baseline is an equal-weight, two-member ensemble extended with a non-bird\n199\tprototypical head. Each 60 s soundscape is split into 12 non-overlapping 5 s windows that feed both members: a\n200\tfrozen Perch v2 backbone read through logit-space MLP probes, and a trained HGNetV2-B0 SED network on\n201\tlog-mel spectrograms. Their 234-species probability vectors are blended equally, post-processed with site/hour\n202\tpriors, and merged with non-bird prototype scores. The whole pipeline runs in ∼64 min, within the 90 min CPU\n203\tlimit. Public LB scores are shown in green.\n204\t\n205\t\f4.1. Methodology\n206\tThe ensemble uses two different backbones. The first is Perch v2 [5] which is frozen with no backbone\n207\ttraining. It emits a 1536-dimensional embedding and 14,795-class logits per 5 s window, which we\n208\tmap onto the 234 competition species (203 direct scientific-name matches, 6 genus proxies, 25 insect\n209\tsonotypes suppressed). The second is an HGNetV2-B0 convolutional SED network operating on log-mel\n210\tspectrograms (256 mel bins, 32 kHz, 2048-point FFT, 313-sample hop).\n211\tFor the Perch member we fit logit-space MLP probes on the frozen embeddings over the 59 fullylabeled soundscapes (of the 66 labeled files) using 5-fold out-of-fold (OOF) GroupKFold cross-validation.\n212\tWe also explored ProtoSSM, a temporal head that refines the per-window probe logits across the twelve\n213\t5 s windows of a soundscape. It uses a bidirectional state-space model and a per-species prototype layer\n214\t[32] with a learned gate against probe logits. The SED member trains HGNetV2-B0 on the focal and\n215\tsoundscape recordings across 4 folds, with spectrogram mixup and a multi-label binary cross-entropy\n216\tloss. The SED member adds dB-scale mel normalization (AmplitudeToDB) and higher mel resolution.\n217\tAt inference each 60 s soundscape is split into 12 non-overlapping 5 s windows, and each member\n218\temits a 234-species probability vector per window. The two members are averaged together with equal\n219\tweight (𝑤Perch = 0.5), with the SED member additionally test-time augmented across its 4 folds. Siteand hour-conditioned priors are then applied as post-processing.\n220\tNon-Bird Prototypical Head Of the 234 competition species, 72 are non-bird taxa outside the\n221\ttraining labels of Perch. To score these species, we introduce a prototypical head [32] that uses the\n222\tPerch backbone. Although Perch was trained exclusively on avian audio, it captures generalized acoustic\n223\tfeatures that help cluster non-bird vocalizations. Of the 72 non-bird taxa, 47 appear in the labeled\n224\t−\n225\tsoundscapes, allowing us to construct positive (𝜇+\n226\t𝑠 ) and negative (𝜇𝑠 ) prototypes by averaging the\n227\tPerch embeddings of all windows where the species is present, and all windows where it is absent,\n228\trespectively. We compute a cosine-difference score for each species 𝑠 and window 𝑡:\n229\tproto\n230\t\n231\t𝑦^𝑡,𝑠\n232\t\n233\t−\n234\t= clip(cos(e𝑡 , 𝜇+\n235\t𝑠 ) − cos(e𝑡 , 𝜇𝑠 ), 0, 1)\n236\t\n237\tFor all non-bird taxa, we first take the SED predictions directly. If a prototype is available for a species,\n238\tfinal =\n239\tthese precomputed scores are merged via element-wise maximum with the SED output: 𝑦^𝑡,𝑠\n240\t(︁\n241\t)︁\n242\tproto\n243\tsed , 𝑦\n244\tmax 𝑦^𝑡,𝑠\n245\t^𝑡,𝑠 . Because the prototype matrices reuse Perch embeddings from the bird head, they\n246\tadd little inference overhead. The full pipeline completes in roughly 64 minutes, well within the\n247\t90-minute CPU limit.\n248\t\n249\t4.2. Leaderboard Results\n250\tThe ensemble performs better than either of its constituents. The frozen Perch probe scores 0.920 and\n251\tthe SED member 0.917, while their blend reaches 0.929 (Table 2). The simplest Perch member uses a\n252\tridge regression probe [33] scoring 0.866 and is replicated in later experiments such as that in Table 6.\n253\tDropping augmentations like the ProtoSSM and the site/hour post-processing leads to only marginal\n254\tdegradation in leaderboard performance.\n255\tAdding the non-bird prototypical head to the MLP-only ensemble raises the public score to 0.931\n256\tand the private score to 0.936. Offline evaluation on the 66 labeled soundscapes shows the prototype\n257\tsubstantially outperforms the SED model alone for non-bird taxa (macro AP 0.895 vs. 0.074). This\n258\tconfirms that the Perch embedding space carries useful information for non-bird species, despite only\n259\tbeing trained on bird data.\n260\tTable 3 contains an ablation of architectural changes to the SED branch of the ensemble. Frontend\n261\tand backbone choices contribute to most of the score gains. dB-scale mel normalization is the largest\n262\tfrontend lever by making quiet and loud recordings comparable, which matters when focal training\n263\tclips and soundscape test clips differ sharply in level. We try a few more elaborate choices like an\n264\tImageNet EfficientNet-B0 SED distilled from Perch v2 embeddings which recovers an identical single\n265\t\n266\t\fTable 2\n267\tBaseline ablations on the BirdCLEF 2026 Kaggle leaderboard. Δ is the public-LB gain over the frozen ridge probe.\n268\tKaggle LB\n269\tConfiguration\n270\t\n271\tpub\n272\t\n273\tpriv\n274\t\n275\tΔ\n276\t\n277\tMembers (standalone)\n278\tPerch v2 + ridge probe (frozen)\n279\tPerch v2 + MLP probes (frozen)\n280\tHGNetV2-B0 SED (4-fold)\n281\t\n282\t0.866\n283\t0.920\n284\t0.917\n285\t\n286\t0.862\n287\t0.918\n288\t0.924\n289\t\n290\t—\n291\t+0.054\n292\t+0.051\n293\t\n294\t0.927\n295\t0.929\n296\t0.922\n297\t\n298\t0.923\n299\t0.925\n300\t0.916\n301\t\n302\t+0.061\n303\t+0.063\n304\t+0.056\n305\t\n306\t0.931\n307\t\n308\t0.936\n309\t\n310\t+0.065\n311\t\n312\tEnsemble (𝑤Perch = 0.5)\n313\twith ProtoSSM head\n314\tMLP-only (drop ProtoSSM)\n315\tno post-processing\n316\tNon-bird prototypical head\n317\tMLP-only + non-bird head\n318\t\n319\tTable 3\n320\tArchitectural ablations from the SED member. Each row is the best public-LB checkpoint at that stage. Δ is\n321\trelative to the row above.\n322\tStage\n323\t\n324\tChange\n325\t\n326\tpub\n327\t\n328\tΔ\n329\t\n330\tBase SED\n331\t+ dB-mel\n332\t+ HGNetV2-B0\n333\t+ 4-fold\n334\t+ priors\n335\t\n336\tEfficientNet-B0 SED (+ post-proc.)\n337\thigh-res mel + AmplitudeToDB\n338\tbackbone swap + NNAudio dB-mel\n339\tlogit-mean over folds\n340\tsite/hour post-processing\n341\t\n342\t0.827\n343\t0.859\n344\t0.906\n345\t0.913\n346\t0.917\n347\t\n348\t—\n349\t+0.032\n350\t+0.047\n351\t+0.007\n352\t+0.004\n353\t\n354\t+ Perch probe\n355\t\n356\tscore-level blend (ensemble)\n357\t\n358\t0.929\n359\t\n360\t+0.012\n361\t\n362\tfold, and an EfficientNetV2-S pretrained on tropical Xeno-Canto audio (Appendix A). Neither buys\n363\tsignificant accuracy, and both add complexity through teacher pipelines or large-scale training.\n364\tOffline validation AUROC anti-correlated with the public leaderboard across 20+ submissions, so we\n365\ttreated every change as a single-variable experiment. A curated record is in Appendix A (Table 9).\n366\t\n367\t5. Token Representations for Bioacoustic Soundscapes\n368\tHaving established a supervised baseline, we ask whether token-based representations can compete with\n369\tit on this leaderboard. We compare codec representations from neural audio codecs, which are trained\n370\tto reconstruct the waveform, versus semantic representations from foundational audio embeddings,\n371\twhich are trained to preserve similarity and separability. We rule out the reconstruction route, then\n372\tturn to the semantic embeddings for their versatility.\n373\t\n374\t5.1. Codec Representations\n375\tWe tested whether a discrete neural audio codec could replace embeddings for species retrieval. We used\n376\tWavTokenizer-large [17] (75 tokens/s, single 4096-code codebook, 24 kHz) as the tokenizer for a sample\n377\tof the bioacoustic data in BirdCLEF 2026. Perch v2 served as the round-trip evaluator. We evaluated this\n378\texperiment on round-trip quality against Perch embeddings and logits, alongside semantic retrieval\n379\ttasks. The first task is a round-trip reconstruction task where we take a clip of audio, pass it through\n380\tthe codec encoder-decoder, and compare the cosine distance of the Perch embeddings under lossless\n381\tand lossy conditions. The second task uses the same round-tripped audio, but this time does a retrieval\n382\ttask over the Perch embeddings. The third task uses the WavTokenizer pooled embeddings directly for\n383\tretrieval on focal recordings. We choose a set of 10 species to analyze the performance.\n384\t\n385\t\fTable 4\n386\tWavTokenizer codec retrieval against its predefined success gates. Every gate is missed by a wide margin. The\n387\tsoundscape phase carried no hard gate; its recall, taken at the most permissive threshold, is indistinguishable\n388\tfrom noise.\n389\tPhase\n390\t\n391\tMetric\n392\t\n393\tTarget\n394\t\n395\tResult\n396\t\n397\tMet?\n398\t\n399\tRound-trip\n400\tRound-trip\n401\tFocal retrieval\n402\t\n403\tPerch embedding cosine\n404\tPrecision@1\n405\tPrecision@10\n406\t\n407\t>0.90\n408\t>0.80\n409\t>0.80\n410\t\n411\t0.313\n412\t0.09\n413\t0.195\n414\t\n415\t×\n416\t×\n417\t×\n418\t\n419\tWavTokenizer codec retrieval failed on every measured account (Table 4). Round-tripping audio\n420\tthrough the codec collapses Perch-embedding cosine similarity (0.313 against the 0.90 gate) and top-1\n421\tspecies accuracy (9%). The resulting encodings are also not useful for semantic search in this domain.\n422\tWavTokenizer was trained on human speech, and breaking round-trip performance down by species\n423\tshows that lower-frequency, speech-like vocalizations survive the codec better than high-frequency\n424\tbird calls (Table 5).\n425\tTable 5\n426\tPer-species round-trip cosine similarity. Speech-like vocalizations (low-frequency tonal calls, dog barks) survive\n427\tthe codec better than the high frequency bird calls.\n428\tSpecies\n429\t\n430\tClass\n431\t\n432\tLesser Snouted Tree Frog\n433\tDomestic Dog\n434\tPale-legged Weeping Frog\n435\tPurplish Jay\n436\tCommon Potoo\n437\tBare-faced Curassow\n438\tRufous Hornero\n439\tGreat Kiskadee\n440\tChestnut-vented Conebill\n441\tWhite-faced Whistling Duck\n442\t\n443\tAmphibia\n444\tMammalia\n445\tAmphibia\n446\tAves\n447\tAves\n448\tAves\n449\tAves\n450\tAves\n451\tAves\n452\tAves\n453\t\n454\tCos sim\n455\t\n456\tTop-1\n457\t\n458\t0.539\n459\t0.423\n460\t0.374\n461\t0.357\n462\t0.340\n463\t0.337\n464\t0.214\n465\t0.201\n466\t0.200\n467\t0.145\n468\t\n469\t25%\n470\t10%\n471\t5%\n472\t5%\n473\t30%\n474\t15%\n475\t0%\n476\t0%\n477\t0%\n478\t0%\n479\t\n480\t5.2. Semantic Representations\n481\tWe measure how well foundational audio embeddings transfer by ranking encoders on the BirdCLEF\n482\ttarget task. We evaluate encoders built largely on vision-transformer architectures, which have not\n483\ttypically appeared as competitive solutions. We screened these encoders on ESC-50 [34] via 5-fold linear\n484\tprobing and separately probed a static-embedding deployment path for cheaper CPU inference; both\n485\tare collected in Appendix D. We finetune with LoRA adapters [35] as a parameter-efficient alternative\n486\tto full updates, since many of these models are large and require significant GPU memory. ESC-50\n487\tis a proxy task, environmental sound classification, and does not rank these encoders on the target\n488\tsoundscape task; however it is a useful source reproducibility check.\n489\tAST [10] is a strong spectrogram-transformer baseline at 95.5% on ESC-50, and one of the first to\n490\texperiment with vision transformers in the audio domain. BEATs [11] is the strongest encoder we tested\n491\tat 95.8%, and is trained using self-supervision and masking. EAT [12] is an efficient audio transformer\n492\tthat extends the BEATs masked-prediction recipe with more aggressive masking and benefits from\n493\tLoRA finetuning. SSAMBA [19] is a variation of AST that uses Mamba layers [18] to approximate\n494\tattention and can in theory scale to much larger token regimes than AST can.\n495\tTo compare these models, we fit a ridge [33] head on each encoder’s frozen embeddings using the\n496\tfocal training recordings. We evaluate using a leave-one-site-out (LOSO) split over the 739 labeled\n497\twindows and report pooled out-of-fold macro AUROC. This validation metric is different from those in\n498\t\n499\t\fthe CNN baseline, but their Kaggle leaderboard measures are provided for consistency in the final test\n500\tset. We add the bioacoustic specialists Perch v2 [5] and BirdNET [4] as anchors.\n501\t\n502\t5.3. Leaderboard Results\n503\tTable 6\n504\tFrozen LOSO ranking vs. deployed Kaggle leaderboard for six encoders on BirdCLEF 2026. AUROC is the\n505\tleaderboard-aligned score from the 9-fold LOSO ridge probe; the public/private LB deploys the same ridge head.\n506\tCPU min/1k is the projected minutes per 1000 60 s clips at 4 vCPU.\n507\tLOSO\n508\t\n509\tKaggle LB\n510\t\n511\tCPU\n512\t\n513\tEncoder\n514\t\n515\tdim\n516\t\n517\tAUROC\n518\t\n519\tpub\n520\t\n521\tpriv\n522\t\n523\tmin/1k\n524\t\n525\tPerch\n526\tBEATs\n527\tBirdNET\n528\tAST\n529\tEAT\n530\tSSAMBA\n531\t\n532\t1536\n533\t768\n534\t1024\n535\t768\n536\t768\n537\t384\n538\t\n539\t0.620\n540\t0.612\n541\t0.588\n542\t0.576\n543\t0.569\n544\t0.563\n545\t\n546\t0.866\n547\t0.777\n548\t0.814\n549\t0.778\n550\t0.780\n551\t0.731\n552\t\n553\t0.862\n554\t0.760\n555\t0.798\n556\t0.768\n557\t0.766\n558\t0.689\n559\t\n560\t11.5\n561\t29.6\n562\t34.5\n563\t38.2\n564\t25.5\n565\t72.5\n566\t\n567\tWe report LOSO training scores and post-competition leaderboard results in Table 6. In local scoring,\n568\tPerch as a bioacoustic specialist barely beats the general encoder BEATs on frozen features, while AST,\n569\tEAT, and SSAMBA cluster at the bottom. However, on the leaderboard, Perch far outranks the other\n570\tmodels, with the other specialist BirdNET coming in second. BirdNET overtakes BEATs despite ranking\n571\tbelow it offline, so our offline ranking is not necessarily a good predictor of leaderboard standing. Perch\n572\tis also the most robust to the public-to-private shift, while the SSL-only SSAMBA degrades the most.\n573\t\n574\t6. Discussion\n575\t6.1. The Geometry of Semantic Tokens\n576\tPerch\n577\t\n578\tBirdNET\n579\t\n580\tBananaquit\n581\t\n582\tThrush\n583\t\n584\tAST\n585\t\n586\tPygmy Owl\n587\t\n588\tEAT\n589\t\n590\tLapwing\n591\t\n592\tBEATs\n593\t\n594\tCicada\n595\t\n596\tGrass Frog\n597\t\n598\tSSAMBA\n599\t\n600\tDog\n601\t\n602\tJaguar\n603\t\n604\tFigure 3: Embedding-space species separability across the six deployed encoders. Two-dimensional PaCMAP\n605\tprojections of frozen embeddings for eight BirdCLEF 2026 species (one point per focal recording, mean-pooled).\n606\t\n607\tTo analyze a feature encoder, we visualize how classes cluster in space. Our results are consistent\n608\twith [6], where birdsong embeddings out-compete AudioMAE and show better separability in a t-SNE\n609\tscatterplot of their embeddings. In Figure 3, we apply PaCMAP to recording centroids across a small\n610\thand-selected set of animals. The specialists are nearly linearly separable, while transformer-based\n611\tmodels conflate several bird species. SSAMBA pools everything together into a blob. The leaderboard\n612\tordering is partly recoverable from 𝑘-nearest-neighbor accuracy over recording centroids used in the\n613\tembedding plot (𝑘 = 10, macro-averaged over the 206 focal species). This kNN ranking recovers the\n614\t\n615\t\f(a) 16 × 16 squares (ViT default)\n616\t\n617\t(b) 128 × 1 full-band columns\n618\tfixed window\n619\t\n620\tfreq\n621\t\n622\tfreq\n623\t\n624\t···\n625\t\n626\ttime\n627\t1,496 tokens / 30 s, window-locked\n628\t\n629\ttime\n630\t3,000 tokens / 30 s, 1-D stream\n631\t\n632\t(c) one continuous stream over a full soundscape\n633\tbird calls = contiguous full-spectrum token runs\n634\t\n635\textends to arbitrary length (60 s+)\n636\t\n637\t···\n638\t\n639\tany sequence model contextualizes the whole stream (attention or a linear-time scan)\n640\t\n641\tFigure 4: Patch geometry on ViT-styled tokenization of spectrograms. (a) The default ViT grid ties tokens to\n642\ta fixed 2-D layout where audio is locked into dimensions of the training data. (b) Full-band 128 × 1 columns\n643\tcollapse the entire spectrum into each token (128 mel bins × 10 ms, one per frame) yielding a 1-D stream. (c)\n644\tBecause the stream is one-dimensional, a sequence model can contextualize an entire soundscape the way a\n645\tlanguage model reads a long prompt.\n646\t\n647\ttop and bottom of the public leaderboard (Perch 0.71, BirdNET 0.58, AST 0.29, EAT 0.27, BEATs 0.23,\n648\tSSAMBA 0.07).\n649\t\n650\t6.2. Toward Sequence Modeling of Arbitrary-Length Audio\n651\tOur experiments and successful solutions on the leaderboard demonstrate that the strongest practical\n652\tsystems are the ones that take advantage of foundational bioacoustic backbones and exploit the newly\n653\tadded supervision signals. These sample-efficient methods use strong foundational encoders and adjust\n654\tfor the domain shift, but all rely on some labeling, weak or otherwise. Between Perch and EAT, there is\n655\tnearly a 9-point gap in public-leaderboard macro AUROC, reflecting Perch’s stronger discriminative\n656\tpower across taxa and species, and Perch is also over 2x faster at inference. The differences are\n657\tno surprise, given that transformer-based models lack the inherent spatial and temporal biases of\n658\tconvolutional neural networks and are forced into token embeddings that were designed to make\n659\tdiscrete data continuous. Additionally, the computational complexity of attention forces engineering\n660\tdecisions that result in a Pareto frontier of potential solutions that scale with the available data and\n661\tcompute.\n662\tOur experimental approach this year failed to exploit the unlabeled soundscapes, with which the\n663\tlabeled soundscapes are distributionally aligned. As in many previous competition years, there is a\n664\tdomain shift between the focal recordings, which contain clear indications of a particular animal’s\n665\tvocalization, and a soundscape, where there can be many different vocalizations at the same time\n666\tat different distances. Transformer-based models can exploit unlabeled data through self-supervised\n667\tobjectives like masked reconstruction. The Bird-MAE authors show that, when trained correctly, the\n668\tlarger parameterization of transformer-based models trained on a specific domain can outperform\n669\tmodels like Perch by a fair margin. However, a limitation of their training methods is that these models\n670\twere given a limited context of audio up to 10 seconds, which aligns with the BirdSet (or AudioSet)\n671\tclassification tasks.\n672\tOne potential path forward would be to build foundational models that can ingest arbitrary length\n673\taudio instead of fixed 5-10 second windows. Figure 4 contrasts two tokenization regimes: the default ViT\n674\t16 × 16 square patches fix the model into a two-dimensional grid, whereas full-band 128 × 1 columns\n675\tyield a one-dimensional token stream that can be ingested into a sequence model. The transformerbased audio models like AST describe some limited experiments with tokenization strategies that favor\n676\ttaller tokens spanning more of the frequency range which achieve comparable or better classification\n677\tperformance, but many models found in shared repositories distribute square patches due to the\n678\t\n679\t\fcomputational savings from starting off a backbone initialized on something like ImageNet. This\n680\trepresentation is well suited to linear-time backbones like Mamba, or other models that scale linearly\n681\twith the number of tokens, in their ability to contextualize a whole soundscape instead of just the\n682\timmediate fragment under consideration. We experimented with continued self-supervised learning\n683\tof a pre-trained SSAMBA [19]. At the scale we could train, however, the result was inconclusive: our\n684\t55k-clip self-supervised run is an order of magnitude smaller than SSL runs in the literature, and none\n685\tof our models reached the supervised BirdSet [8] baselines (Appendix E).\n686\tDespite there being 177 hours of soundscape audio, these are distributed across a much smaller\n687\tnumber of sites. The time and place then becomes a useful deductive tool that could be implicitly\n688\tencoded into a backbone. Another natural direction is to encourage few-shot behavior by creating\n689\tquestion and answer pairs joined by separator tokens, and to propagate back signal through a head that\n690\tlearns to attend to similar patterns. This might exhibit itself as a prototypical retrieval system where\n691\tclasses with only a few examples can be used to modulate how the model perceives tokens in context.\n692\tAdditionally, it might be viable to build a multi-modal model where language describing the taxonomy\n693\tand the audible properties of the soundscape could be trained with a CLIP loss to aid in active learning\n694\tloops. Despite the leaderboard’s affinity for small, fast models, larger and more expressive models might\n695\tstill exploit low-resource class data well enough to distill into a smaller deployable model.\n696\t\n697\t7. Conclusion\n698\tThis year we pursued a supervised baseline built to the community’s best practices, and a study of\n699\twhether token-based representations could compete with it on the same leaderboard. The baseline\n700\tcarried the result, with an equal-weight ensemble of a frozen Perch v2 backbone and a trained HGNetV2B0 sound-event-detection network reaching 0.929 at rank 1962 on private leaderboard within the\n701\t90-minute CPU budget. Adding in a prototypical head for insects brough this up to 0.936 at rank 1894.\n702\tThe representational thread was less conclusive. The codec route failed on bioacoustic retrieval due to\n703\trepresentational constraints, the semantic embeddings transferred only modestly due to domain gap,\n704\tand the linear-time state-space alternative remained inconclusive at the scale we could train. However,\n705\twe look forward to foundational bioacoustic systems that exploit unlabeled data and make use of\n706\tlow-resource classes, in a domain where expertise is limited and conservation needs are urgent. We are\n707\tcurious to see how artificial intelligence develops in service of conservation, ideally in ways that help\n708\tus quantify and act on positive change.\n709\t\n710\tAcknowledgments\n711\tWe thank the Data Science at Georgia Tech Applied Research Competitions group (DS@GT ARC) for\n712\ttheir support. This research was supported in part through research cyberinfrastructure resources and\n713\tservices provided by the Partnership for an Advanced Computing Environment (PACE) at the Georgia\n714\tInstitute of Technology, Atlanta, Georgia, USA [36].\n715\t\n716\tDeclaration on Generative AI\n717\tAI-assisted tools (e.g., Claude Code, Codex) were used during the development of this work to aid in\n718\tprogramming, debugging, grammar and spelling checks, literature review, and experimentation. All\n719\texperiments were designed and configured by the authors, all results were manually verified, and all\n720\tscientific interpretations and conclusions reflect the authors’ own judg